<section id="intro" class="chapter">
    <h2>1. Introduction: Supply in the Empire’s Far-Flung Fronts</h2>
    <p>
        From Manchuria to Burma to the scattered islands of the Pacific, Japanese truck crews faced  
        brutal terrain, constant mechanical shortages, and dangerous combat zones. Their work was  
        essential to maintaining the Imperial war effort.
    </p>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/3/3f/Toyota_GB_Military_Truck.jpg" alt="Toyota GB">
        <p><em>Toyota GB — a standard truck of the Transport Corps.</em></p>
    </div>
</section>

<section id="vehicles" class="chapter">
    <h2>2. Vehicles of the Imperial Transport Corps</h2>

    <h3>Toyota GB</h3>
    <p>Widely used, though limited by wartime material shortages.</p>

    <h3>Type 94 6-Wheel Truck</h3>
    <p>Served infantry divisions; known for difficult maintenance in tropical climates.</p>

    <h3>Nissan 80</h3>
    <p>A basic but dependable vehicle for courier and transport duties.</p>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/5/5f/Nissan_80_japan_truck.jpg" alt="Nissan 80">
    </div>
</section>

<section id="routes" class="chapter">
    <h2>3. Routes Across Asia & the Pacific</h2>

    <h3>Burma & India Front</h3>
    <p>Monsoons washed out roads, creating knee-deep mud and landslides.</p>

    <h3>Pacific Islands</h3>
    <p>Narrow jungle tracks and coral roads destroyed tires and suspensions quickly.</p>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/d/d1/IJA_motor_pool_Pacific.jpg" alt="IJA Motor Pool">
    </div>

    <h3>Manchuria</h3>
    <p>Cold winters caused fuel to gel and engines to crack without proper warming.</p>
</section>

<section id="safety" class="chapter">
    <h2>4. Safety, Security & Survival</h2>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Camouflage nets</strong> required during stops.</li>
        <li><strong>Minimal headlights:</strong> enemy aircraft were common.</li>
        <li><strong>Carry personal ration kits</strong> for isolated islands.</li>
        <li><strong>Insect nets & quinine</strong> essential in malaria regions.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section id="maintenance" class="chapter">
    <h2>5. Field Repairs & Improvised Solutions</h2>

    <h3>Tropical Problems</h3>
    <p><strong>Humidity damage:</strong> Dry electrical parts over fire-heated metal plates.</p>
    <p><strong>Mud-filled brakes:</strong> Clean with bamboo scrapers.</p>

    <h3>Fuel Shortages</h3>
    <p>Crews often mixed low-octane substitutes or used reclaimed oils.</p>
</section>

<section id="life" class="chapter">
    <h2>6. Life in the Convoy</h2>
    <p>
        Drivers often lived in makeshift huts or slept under their trucks.  
        Harsh discipline, scarce supplies, and constant movement defined their world.
    </p>

    <blockquote>
        “A driver must move forward, no matter the jungle, no matter the night.”
    </blockquote>

    <div class="illustration">
        <img src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/0/00/IJA_truck_convoy_1942.jpg" alt="IJA convoy">
    </div>
</section>

<footer>
    Imperial Transport Corps Guide — In honor of the men who drove the Empire’s supply lines.
</footer>

